THE MENU



The BAS does not use standard Amiga Dos type menus or the mouse
(except in particular ways, which will be discussed) but is based
almost entirely on key presses.  In order to keep the programme simple
and fast the keyboard has been assigned the appropriate commands and
you should find after a very short time using the software, that
producing Titles and credits will be second nature.  The main menu has
various sub-sections which are accessible by pressing keys F1 to F10
at the top of the Amiga keyboard.  These in turn utilise further
similar key presses to perform a specific task, but in all cases there
are on screen prompts telling you what keys to press, so you cannot
really go wrong.





The programme comes with instructional text which can be immediately
Šviewed by pressing F1 on presentation of the main screen menu.  This
Šinformal but instructional copy should give you a good idea of the
Šprogrammes capabilities and at the same time provide you with copy to
Šexperiment with, feel free to chop, change or abuse the text and when
Šyou've had enough, clear the screen and get to work.  It could be said
Šthat this software does not really require a manual, and that is true
Šas the presence of a HELP screen and numerous simple on screen prompts
Šshould be all you need.

Here is a summary of available commands:

F1 - VERTICAL SCROLL: All the numbered keys on the top row and numeric
Škeyboard on the right, control the speed of scroll, ranging from the
Šslowest speed 1, to the fastest 9.


F2 - HORIZONTAL SCROLL: Same as above, but text will always scroll
Šfrom right to left of the screen.

F3 - EDIT TEXT: Key commands available are:

        Arrow keys: move cursor 1 character.
        Shift + Left or Right arrow keys: Move cursor 1 word.
        Shift + Up or Down arrow keys: Move text 1 line.
        Shift +Delete Key: clears all text on screen.
        Numeric keypad: Pageup, Pagedown, Home, End.
        F1 - F3: Set colour of subsequent text.
        F5: Toggle shadow on/off.
        F6: Pound sign (£). F7: Copyright symbol (  ).
        F8:  Left justification.
        F9:  Centre justification.
        F10: Right justification.
        Left shift key + F1 - F10:  Select font from bank A.
        Right shift key + F1 - F10: Select font from bank B.
        Esc: To return to the editor.
        Help key: Shows HELP screen with key prompts.

F4 - SET SCROLLER PARAMETERS: Up and Down arrow keys move the left
Šmargin marker.  Left and Right arrow keys move the right margin
Šmarker.  This allows you to set the screen text width for vertical
Šscrolling only.  Text can therefore be positioned anywhere on the
Šscreen.

By holding down the Shift key + Up/Down arrow keys, a marker can be
Špositioned to indicate where the text will horizontally enter the
Šscreen.  The marker indicates the top of the text.


F1: This toggles either a continuous or single scroll.  A continual
Šscroll is best used for displaying information.  Whilst the single
scroll is best for credits and titles for video work.  The text will
pass through once and scroll off the screen leaving the background
colour.


NB: After setting your margins in either vertical or horizontal mode
you must first return to the edit screen (F3) in order to re-format
the text for scrolling purposes.

F5 - SET COLOURS:

        F1: Set colour 0 (Background colour)
        F2: Set colour 1 (Pen 1)
        F3: Set colour 2 (Pen 2)
        F4: Set colour 3 (Pen 3 or shadow colour)

Look closely at the Default text colour settings.  The background
colour is a rich blue.  Colour 1 or Pen 1 has been set to a light blue
and is used for most of the copy.  However, Colour 2 or Pen 2 is set
to a very light green and has been used to highlight certain key
words.  For the drop shadow on the lettering, Colour 3 or Pen 3 has
been defined as almost black. Note well that if you do not want to use
a drop shadow effect on your text, then Colour 3 could be used as
another highlight shade.

The colours are set using a simple principal of altering Red, Green
and Blue values, by pressing the R, G and B keys on the keyboard.  In
principal any one of 4096 colours or shades are assignable to the keys
F1 to F3.

The way the codes work are relatively simple.  Take just one pure
colour ie. Red, assuming the Green and the Blue values are set to 0,
then by pressing the R key on the keyboard, you can start at 100
(which is the darkest red) through to F00 (the brightest red) ie. 100,
200, 300, 400, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900, A00, B00, C00, D00, E00, F00.
Obviously, the same progression will apply to Green, ie. 010 to 0F0
and Blue 001 to 00F. By combining these codes many other colours can
be achieved.  Also by holding down the shift and pressing the
appropriate colour key, it is possible to work back through the colour
codes.

Here are some to be getting on with:-

        Black           000 (or colour zero - genlockable)
        White           FFF
        Yellow          FF0     Powder Yellow           D80
        Orange          F80     Powder Blue             047
        Purple          A2A     Powder Green            09B
        Brown           950     Shadow Green            050
        Red             F00     Shadow Blue             068
        Green           0F0     Shocking Pink           F09
        Blue            00F
        Grey            375     For those of you that are curious
        Cyan            07C     about the code.  It is all just
        Pink            E08     Hex to me.


F6 - SET SHADOW: By utilising the arrow keys a drop shadow can be
positioned quite effectively under your main text.  There are some
limitations, but this should not really present any problems in
practise.  Remember that in F3 (Edit text) mode, pressing F5 will
toggle the shadow on or off.

F7 - SET SPACING: Quite simple really.  All you have to do is press
the Right arrow key to space the characters in your text further
apart, and by pressing the Left arrow key, bring the characters closer
together.  The Down arrow key will space the words in your text
further apart , and by pressing the Up arrow key, bring the words
closer together.  This is a global setting and will affect your text,
it cannot be applied to single letters or words.  This is not true of
kerning as such, but nevertheless can give interesting results.

F8 - DISK MENU; F1: Load Text - presents you with a listing of
available files from the disk that has been accessed.  Use arrow keys
to choose named file and press enter or return.

F2: Save Text - presents you with a listing of available files from
the disk that has been accessed.  Type name of file, then press enter
or return to save file to disk.  When saving a file to disk, all
parameters and setting are also saved and can be loaded again for
further editing.

F3: Delete File - Simply gives you the option to delete unwanted files
from your data-disk.

F4: Format Disk - This option allows you to create a special data-disk
for saving your files.  Because BAS uses it's own unique code, in
order to save work you must only use disks that have been formatted by
this option.  A very large number of files can be stored on one disk.
It is also possible to copy or back-up your data-disks using Duplicate
or DiskCopy from Workbench.

0 - 3: By pressing any of the numbered keys from 0 to 3 a drive can be
selected for any of the above options.  Drive DF0: is the default.

F9 - SET KEYBOARD TYPE: The programme defaults to a Great Britain
Keymap.  For those of you with American (USA) keyboards, press F2.  A
USA keyboard has a # symbol above the 3 instead of a £ sign.

EXTRA INFO: The mouse has a particular feature within the programme.
For instance, by holding down the Left mouse button whilst in  EDIT
TEXT mode, the flashing cursor can be made to disappear.  This allows
you to use still text for video titling.  Also when in active Vertical
or Horizontal scrolling, by holding down the left mouse button the
previous lower speed can be accessed.  Likewise holding down the right
mouse button will access the next highest scroll speed.


INTERLACE & FLICKER: The software operates in High Resolution full
Overscan mode and produces an interlaced screen.  It was primarily
designed to be used with Video, which is an interlaced signal itself.
You will probably experience varying degrees of shimmer and flicker
when viewing  the scroll on your monitor.  This is most apparent when
scrolling small text at fast speeds.  It is highly unlikely that you
will have any serious application for this.  We would suggest that
careful choice of colours, font and scrolling speeds will get around
most display applications.

THE THINGS YOU CANNOT DO...YET!

        1. BAS will not multi-task with any other software.

        2. It is not possible to install the programme onto a
           hard-disk, or copy the software for back-up purposes.

        3. You cannot mix different fonts within the same file.

        4. At present the software does not support loading in of
           ASCII files from other word processing programmes.

        5. You cannot import other fonts into the programme.

        6. The Big Alternative Scroller will not make you a cup
           of tea, but it should make producing titles and credits
           much easier.



        We will hope to address many of the above points in Version 2
        of the programme, in the meantime HAPPY SCROLLING.


        IMPORTANT NOTE: When using the programme to produce titles for
         video, please make sure that you are already genlocked before
         booting-up the system.  This will ensure that you will have a
         glitch free picture.

